{:itonami.blueprint/id "cloud-itonami-isic-932"
 :itonami.blueprint/name "Amusement and Recreation Facility Operations Coordination"
 :itonami.blueprint/isic-rev4 "932"
 :itonami.blueprint/domain :services/amusement-facility-coordination
 :itonami.blueprint/license "AGPL-3.0"
 :itonami.blueprint/social-impact [:operational-efficiency :guest-safety :facility-safety]
 :itonami.blueprint/governor :amusementfacilityops-governor
 :itonami.blueprint/robotics false
 :itonami.blueprint/required-technologies [:identity :forms :dmn :bpmn :audit-ledger]
 :itonami.blueprint/status :public-oss
 :itonami.blueprint/maturity :implemented
 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "DefaultAdvisor (amusementfacilityops.advisor/Advisor protocol seam over
 the five unchanged per-op advisor fns) |- amusementfacilityops.governor
 (three HARD, permanent checks: facility-unverified, effect-not-propose,
 scope-exclusion), a REAL compiled langgraph-clj StateGraph
 (langgraph.graph, amusementfacilityops.operation/build), append-only
 audit ledger (amusementfacilityops.store/ledger + append-ledger!,
 MemStore). Fixes a prior gap: operation.cljc's own docstring claimed
 'langgraph-clj StateGraph' but the actual code was a hand-rolled
 (-> state intake advise govern decide (case action ...)) threading
 pipeline -- zero require of langgraph.graph, zero use of
 state-graph/add-node/compile-graph anywhere in the file -- and its
 `decide` step could never actually reach the `commit` step (dead code)
 while amusementfacilityops.phase's auto-commit table was defined and
 unit-tested in isolation but never consulted by any decision logic.
 Now: a genuinely compiled StateGraph (:intake -> :advise -> :govern ->
 :decide -+-> :commit / :request-approval -> :commit / :hold) with
 interrupt-before #{:request-approval} + in-memory checkpointer for real
 human-in-the-loop resume, and amusementfacilityops.phase's
 auto-commits-at-phase? genuinely gates the :commit route. The Governor
 (three HARD, permanent, un-overridable checks) and the append-only
 audit ledger were already genuinely wired in the pre-graph pipeline
 (store/append-ledger! was real, not dead code) -- both preserved
 unchanged. Five ops (:schedule-facility-booking /
 :coordinate-maintenance-schedule-proposal / :coordinate-supply-request /
 :coordinate-guest-services-logistics / :flag-safety-concern), all
 :effect :propose only. :flag-safety-concern ALWAYS escalates to a human
 operator via the compiled graph's :request-approval node
 (interrupt-before, checkpoint-based resume), proven end-to-end by
 test/amusementfacilityops/operation_test.clj (commit / hard-hold
 (unverified facility) / scope-exclusion hold / phase-hold /
 escalate-approve / escalate-reject through the REAL compiled graph),
 plus a `clojure -M:dev:run` demo runner producing real ledger entries
 for every scenario. Test suite rewritten from an unfalsifiable
 assert+println harness (0 deftest/is, unconditionally printed 'All
 tests passed!' regardless of whether the prior assertions held) to real
 clojure.test deftest/is across advisor/governor/phase/store/operation."}
